---
The First Stone Accord is Midgaard's founding document — a mutual-defense compact between three groups at the convergence of dangerous trade routes.
The three founding parties were the River Factors (grain merchants controlling barge traffic), the Upland Syndicate (ore and timber traders from northern forest routes), and the Temple Compact (pilgrim-route chaplains providing neutral arbitration).
The Accord established one practical principle expressed in street design: all roads must return to a watched square. This is why Midgaard's grid feels repetitive — repetition was a security technology, not an architectural preference.
The Accord was not a constitution and not an ideology. It was a mutual-defense pact that grew from geographic necessity: the site where multiple dangerous routes converged required managed traffic, dispute resolution, and overnight security.
Each founding party contributed to a shared militia and agreed to submit disputes to public tribunal rather than private violence.
The physical expression — roads converging on watched squares — became Midgaard's architectural DNA; every subsequent governance layer has been built on top of this structural commitment.
The Accord's founding text established three obligations that persist in modified form through all subsequent governance layers: road security, dispute tribunal, and militia contribution.
Every major governance addition — Lantern Reforms, Violet Compact, Ash-and-Iron emergency law — was a response to a specific crisis that the original Accord's framework could not address, layered on top rather than replacing.
Midgaard is therefore not a city built on a single ideology but an accretion of crisis responses to pressures generated by its geographic position.
The First Stone Accord is cited by the Continuity faction as the legitimating precedent for all subsequent charter law; the Reckoning faction uses it as a baseline against which to measure how far later governance layers departed from the Accord's founding spirit.
The Accord predates written registry; its terms were oral for the founding generation and codified in the first written charter during the Standardization Century.

flags MIDGAARD
---
The Accord's three-party structure established distributed authority that Midgaard's governance layers
have preserved even as the original parties dissolved into modern institutions. The Lantern Reforms'
standardization of paving marks, posted tariffs, and night patrol routes were the first formal
elaboration of the Accord's "watched square" principle into a legible city-wide system. Continuity
faction: the Accord is the constitutional source from which all legitimate charter law derives.
Reckoning faction critique: founding parties held legitimate grievances the tribunal mechanism
suppressed rather than resolved; the display version omits the militia contribution clause's original
reciprocal protection language that was not honored during the Ash-and-Iron years for external
populations. The Charter Sovereignty office's authority to refuse annexation petitions derives from
the Accord's founding premise: sovereignty of the converging routes.

flags KOWLOON
---
The Neon Covenant was written with full awareness of the First Stone Accord's structure and deliberately
diverged from it on founding parties: six founding houses rather than three, preventing any two-party
coalition from dominating. The "public tribunal rather than private violence" principle was preserved
as "one square, final judgment," but Kowloon added the physical covenant stone as material anchor for
institutional memory. The Jade Magistracy reads the Accord as evidence that institutional design is
path-dependent: Midgaard's current governance complexity traces to the Accord's simplicity, and that
simplicity created structural gaps requiring additional layers. Kowloon considers the Accord a
legitimate founding instrument but not a transferable model—different founding positions required
different founding solutions.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's founding charter explicitly cites the First Stone Accord as the origin point of the governance
tradition it both inherits and critiques. Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant clause states it supplements
the Accord's public-tribunal principle by specifying that no party may be stripped of civic identity
through registry reclassification before their case is heard—addressing the Ash-and-Iron failure where
the Violet Compact processed tribunal defendants as "arcane material" before proceedings were complete.
Kiess's three-power governance mirrors the Accord's three founding parties but with formal mutual-
censure mechanisms the original Accord lacked. The Syndic Council holds the obsidian disc bearing
the Spirebound Conclave's seal alongside a copy of the Accord text—a pairing asserting institutional
continuity between the Accord's founding and the Conclave's exploitation of the governance systems
it generated.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's founding charter explicitly modeled itself on the First Stone Accord's structure: distributed
founding parties, public tribunal, militia obligation. The modeling was aspirational rather than
practical—Rakuen's founding population arrived under Midgaard's "resettled south" mechanism rather
than choosing the site for its strategic value. The Southmark Petition cited the Accord-derived
structure as evidence of institutional compatibility with Midgaard. Midgaard refused on ledger-
compliance grounds; Rakuen converted its accounting systems to Midgaard ledger standards; the next
refusal cited different grounds. The Bloom Council's constitutional scholars hold that Rakuen's Accord
inheritance gives it a stronger claim to institutional recognition than the Ash Plea's humanitarian
framing ever could—because it appeals to Midgaard's self-conception as a founding institution rather
than to Midgaard's charity.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Ledger Houses predate the First Stone Accord and acknowledge it as a later development in
the governance tradition they participate in rather than as a founding precedent. The Strandline
Compact was formalized during the Fracture Era—contemporaneous with Midgaard's Violet Compact period,
not with the First Stone Accord. Mafdet's maritime legal tradition derives from the Keepers of Measure's
Littoral Branch rather than the inland charter tradition the Accord established. Mafdet's formal
acknowledgment of the Accord is diplomatic: it cites the Accord as the legitimate founding of
Midgaard's governance authority while maintaining that the Accord's jurisdiction ends at the coast.
The Swift Court's standard international cargo contract oath includes "valid under all charter
traditions descended from the First Stone Accord"—acknowledging the Accord's precedential authority
over inland systems while specifying it as one tradition among others.

flags MIDGAARD HUMAN
---
Human governance doctrine treats the First Stone Accord as the foundational text from which all
legitimate authority derives. The three founding parties were human-majority institutions; the Accord
was designed for and by humans managing human commerce. The governance tradition the Accord established
has no explicit framework for non-human civic participants or knowledge systems. This absence is the
structural source of every classification failure in Midgaard's subsequent history: when non-human
populations arrived in quantity—Ashborn, Khephari corridor communities, Deltari refugees—the intake
system had no founding-document basis for treating them as civic actors rather than managed populations.
Continuity faction: subsequent amendments have addressed the Accord's gaps. Reckoning faction:
amendments layered on a founding document excluding non-human civic standing produce systems that
formally include non-humans while structurally treating them as exceptions. The debate is unresolved.
